    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-05-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-05-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="285"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d285">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.503193/11</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 2744</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-05-26">May 26,
                            1934</date>.<lb/>[Received July 2.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to the Legation’s
                    despatch No. 2715, May 9, 1934,<note n="60" xml:id="d285fn60">See footnote 44,
                            <ref target="#pg_377">p. 377</ref>.</note> concerning Mr. Monnet’s
                    scheme for inducing foreign financial investments in China, and to enclose for
                    the Department’s information a copy of the Nanking Counselor of Legation’s
                    despatch to the Legation No. 327–Diplomatic, May 21, 1934.<note n="61"
                        xml:id="d285fn61">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. Peck quotes an unnamed American newspaper representative as reporting that
                    Mr. Suma, Secretary of the Japanese Legation, had expressed to him gratification
                    at having learned that the Japanese Foreign Office had adopted some of his, Mr.
                    Suma’s, views in regard to Mr. Monnet’s proposal. Mr. Suma is said to view Mr.
                    Monnet’s proposal with disfavor because China should first provide settlement of
                    its outstanding indebtedness (presumably Japanese); because it violates the
                    understanding underlying the International Consortium of 1920; and because all
                    money invested in China, even that for economic purposes, would actually be used
                    to achieve political ends.</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Nelson Trusler Johnson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
